IMAGE
An image and a container runtime (Docker engine) are needed to create a container
 # an image is like a blueprint or template, and the building material, while a container is an instance of that blueprint or template.
 #  The image provides all the necessary instructions and dependencies for the container to run. 
 # A Docker image is a file. An image never changes; you can not edit an existing file. 
 # Creating a new image happens by starting from a base image and adding new layers to it. 
* docker image ls #list all image
 This image file is built from an instructional file named Dockerfile that is parsed when you run docker image build run:
 (syntax) * docker buildx build [OPTIONS] PATH | URL | 
dockerfile contains the blueprint to create images, just like images are for containers, the only difference is that Dockerfile is written by the user and image by the machine

Container​
Containers contain the application and what is required to execute it (dependencies); they can be started, stopped, and interacted with. 
They are isolated environments on the host machine, capable of interacting with each other and with the host machine itself via defined methods (TCP/UDP).
* docker container ls -a #lists all available containers, without -a flag, it just lists the running containers
* docker ps -a #short hand 
*  docker container rm 3d # imagine container's ID is 3d4bab29dd67, using the first few characters of an ID
* docker container rm id1 id2 id3 #multiple argument

The CLI interacts with the "Docker Engine" which is made up of 3 components:
 - the Docker daemon, the Rest API, and the CLI client(command line interface)

